      "writtenOn": "2016-07-28T17:24:09Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I certainly agree that it\u0027s a great idea to have the same syntax for the \u003coptions\u003e in \"-debug \u003coptions\u003e\" and the use of the same \u003coptions\u003e syntax in the console command.\n\nHowever, I can\u0027t get my head around the -debug-\u003coptions\u003e part.  Are you sure you\u0027re comfortable with, say:\n\n-debug--opt\n\nas allowable syntax (note the two dashes between debug and opt -- this is a synonym, AFAICT for -debug-no-opt).  This really strikes me as deciding on a user interface on the basis of how efficiently it can be coded, rather than how understandable or error prone it might be.\n\nIf we can\u0027t resolve this between ourselves, could I suggest we ask some third party to arbitrate?  Maybe somebody with some user-experience credentials?  Any suggestions?",
